# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: albany-new-york
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:albany-new-york/1790-united-states-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:albany-new-york/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:albany-new-york/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:albany-new-york/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:albany-new-york/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:albany-new-york/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:albany-new-york/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:albany-new-york/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:albany-new-york/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:albany-new-york/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:albany-new-york/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:albany-new-york/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:albany-new-york/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:albany-new-york/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:albany-new-york/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:albany-new-york/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:albany-new-york/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:albany-new-york/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:albany-new-york/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:albany-new-york/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:albany-new-york/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:albany-new-york/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:albany-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:albany-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:albany-new-york/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:albany-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:albany-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:albany-new-york/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:albany-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:albany-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:albany-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:albany-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:albany-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:albany-new-york/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:albany-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:albany-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:albany-new-york/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:albany-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:albany-new-york/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:albany-new-york/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:albany-new-york/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:albany-new-york/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:albany-new-york/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:albany-new-york/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:albany-new-york/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:albany-new-york/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:albany-new-york/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:albany-new-york/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:albany-new-york/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:albany-new-york/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:albany-new-york/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:albany-new-york/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:albany-new-york/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:albany-new-york/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:albany-new-york/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:albany-new-york/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:albany-new-york/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:albany-new-york/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] In 1853 the country contains 89 telegraph lines that stretched 23,261 miles (37,435 km).
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] When published in 1854, the country had an estimated 30,000 miles (48,000 km) of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:albany-new-york/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The oldest city in New York, the City of Albany is the economic and cultural core of New York State's Capital District.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The Capital District is a metropolitan area including the nearby cities and suburbs of Colonie, Troy, Schenectady, and Saratoga Springs.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] With an estimated 1.3 million residents, the Capital District is one of the most populous metropolitan areas and is the fastest-growing region in Upstate New York.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The area that ultimately became Albany was originally inhabited by Algonquian-speaking Mohicans.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The area was settled by Dutch colonists, who built Fort Nassau in 1614 for fur trading and Fort Orange in 1624.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In 1664, the English took over the Dutch settlements, renaming the city "Albany" in honor of the Scottish title of the Duke of York (later James II of England and Ireland and James VII of Scotland): the Duke of Albany.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The city was officially chartered in 1686 under English rule.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] It became the capital of New York in 1797 after the formation of the United States.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is the oldest surviving settlement of the original British Thirteen Colonies north of Virginia.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In the late 18th century and throughout most of the 19th, Albany was a center of trade and transportation.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The city lies toward the north end of the navigable Hudson River.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] It was the original eastern terminus of the Erie Canal and was home to some of the earliest railroads in the world.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In the 1920s, a powerful political machine controlled by the Democratic Party emerged in Albany.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's population shrank because of urban sprawl and suburbanization in the latter part of the 20th century.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In the 1990s, the New York State Legislature approved for the city a US$234 million building and renovation plan, which spurred downtown redevelopment.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Since 2020, the economy of Albany and the surrounding Capital District has been directed toward artificial intelligence, AI-based photonics, quantum computing hardware manufacturing, nanotechnology, and digital electronics.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The Hudson River area was originally inhabited by Algonquian-speaking Mohicans, who called it *Pempotowwuthut-Muhhcanneuw*, meaning "the fireplace of the Mohican nation".
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Based to the west along the Mohawk River, the Iroquoian-speaking Mohawk called it *skahnéhtati*, also transliterated to Sche-negh-ta-da, "through the pine woods", referring to the path they took there.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] According to Hendrick Aupaumut, the Mohicans came to the area from the north and the west.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] They settled along the Mahicannituck River, which is now called the Hudson River, and called themselves the *Muh-he-con-neok*, the "People of the Waters That Are Never Still".
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The Mohawks, one of the Five Nations of the Iroquois Confederacy, were based in the Mohawk valley and noted for their fur trading and their access to trade between the Iroquois and other nations.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The Mohawk became strong trading partners with the Dutch and English.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] It is likely that the area was visited by European fur traders perhaps as early as 1540, but the extent and duration of those visits are unclear.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Permanent European claims began when Englishman Henry Hudson, exploring for the Dutch East India Company on the *Half Moon* (Dutch: *Halve Maen*), reached the area in 1609, claiming it for the United Netherlands.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In 1614, Hendrick Christiaensen built Fort Nassau on Castle Island (now called Port of Albany), in the Hudson River.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The fort acted as a fur-trading post and was the first documented European structure in present-day Albany.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Commencement of the fur trade provoked hostility from the French colony in Canada and among the natives, all of whom vied to control the trade.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In 1618, a flood ruined Fort Nassau, but the Dutch replaced it with Fort Orange on the mainland in 1624.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Both forts were named in honor of the leading family of the Dutch Revolt, members of the House of Orange-Nassau.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Fort Orange and the surrounding area were incorporated as the village of Beverwijck (English: Beaverwick or Beaver District) in 1652, and the city of Albany in 1686.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In these early decades of trade, the Dutch, Mohican, and Mohawk developed relations that reflected differences among their three cultures.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is one of the oldest surviving European settlements from the original Thirteen Colonies and the longest continuously chartered city in the United States.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] When New Netherland was captured by the English in 1664, the name was changed from *Beverwijck* to *Albany* in honor of Prince James, Duke of Albany (later King James VII/II).
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Duke of Albany was a Scottish title given since 1398, generally to a younger son of the King of Scots.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The name is ultimately derived from *Alba*, the Gaelic name for Scotland.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The Dutch briefly regained Albany in August 1673 and renamed the city *Willemstadt*; the English took permanent possession in 1674 with the Treaty of Westminster.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany was formally chartered as a municipality by provincial Governor Thomas Dongan on July 22, 1686.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The Dongan Charter was virtually identical in content to the charter awarded to the city of New York three months earlier.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Dongan created Albany as a strip of land 1 mile (1.6 km) wide and 16 miles (26 km) long.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Over the years Albany would lose much of the land to the west and annex land to the north and south.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] At this point, Albany had a population of about 500 people.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In 1754, representatives of seven British North American colonies met in the *Stadt Huys*, Albany's city hall, for the Albany Congress; Benjamin Franklin of Pennsylvania presented the Albany Plan of Union there, which was the first formal proposal to unite the colonies.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Although it was never adopted by Parliament, it was an important precursor to the United States Constitution.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The same year, the French and Indian War, the fourth in a series of wars dating back to 1689, began.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] It ended in 1763 with French defeat, resolving a situation that had been a constant threat to Albany and held back its growth.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Tories and prisoners of war were often jailed in the *Stadt Huys* alongside common criminals.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In 1776, Albany native Philip Livingston signed the Declaration of Independence.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] During and after the Revolutionary War, Albany County saw a great increase in real estate transactions.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] After the 1777 colonial victory at the Battle of Saratoga, the upper Hudson Valley was generally at peace as the war raged on elsewhere.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Prosperity was soon seen all over Upstate New York.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Migrants from Vermont and Connecticut began flowing in, noting the advantages of living on the Hudson and trading at Albany, while being only a few days' sail from New York City.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany reported a population of 3,498 in the first national census in 1790, an increase of almost 700% since its chartering.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] On November 17, 1793, fire broke out at a stable belonging to Leonard Gansevoort, destroying 26 homes on Broadway, Maiden Lane, James Street, and State Street.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Three were arrested and charged with arson: Pompey, a man belonging to Matthew Visscher; Dinah, a 14-year-old girl belonging to Volkert P.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Douw; and Bet, a 12-year-old girl belonging to Philip S.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] On January 6, 1794, the three were sentenced to death.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Governor George Clinton issued a temporary stay of execution, but Dinah and Bet were executed by hanging on March 14, and Pompey on April 11, 1794.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In 1797, the state capital was moved permanently to Albany.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] From statehood to this date, the Legislature had frequently moved the state capital between Albany, Kingston, Poughkeepsie, and the city of New York.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is the tenth-oldest state capital in the United States and the second-oldest city that is a state capital, after Santa Fe, New Mexico.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany has been a center of transportation for much of its history.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In the late 18th and early 19th centuries, Albany saw development of the turnpike and by 1815, Albany was the turnpike center of the state.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The development of Simeon De Witt's gridded block system in 1794—which renamed streets that had originally named after the British royal family with names of birds and mammals instead—was intersected by these major arterials coming out of Albany, cutting through the city at unexpected angles.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The construction of the turnpike, in conjunction with canal and railroad systems, made Albany the hub of transportation for pioneers going to Buffalo and the Michigan Territory in the early and mid-19th century.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In 1807, Robert Fulton initiated a steamboat line from New York City to Albany, the first successful enterprise of its kind anywhere in the world.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] By 1810, with 10,763 people, Albany was the tenth-largest urban place in the nation.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The town and village north of Albany known as "the Colonie" was annexed in 1815.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In 1825 the Erie Canal was completed, forming a continuous water route from the Great Lakes to New York City.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Unlike the current Barge Canal, which ends at nearby Waterford, the original Erie Canal ended at Albany; Lock 1 was north of Colonie Street.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The Canal emptied into a 32-acre (13 ha) man-made lagoon called the Albany Basin, which was Albany's main port from 1825 until the Port of Albany-Rensselaer opened in 1932.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In 1829, while working as a professor at the Albany Academy, Joseph Henry, widely regarded as "the foremost American scientist of the 19th century", built the first electric motor.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Three years later, he discovered electromagnetic self-induction (the SI unit for which is now the henry).
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] He went on to be the first Secretary of the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In the 1830 and 1840 censuses, Albany was ranked as the ninth-largest urban place in the nation; it dropped back to tenth in 1850.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] This was the last time the city was one of the top ten largest urban places in the nation.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany also has significant history with rail transport, as the location of two major regional railroad headquarters.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The Delaware and Hudson Railway was headquartered in Albany at what is now the SUNY System Administration Building.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In 1853, Erastus Corning, a noted industrialist and Albany's mayor from 1834 to 1837, consolidated ten railroads stretching from Albany to Buffalo into the New York Central Railroad (NYCRR), headquartered in Albany until Cornelius Vanderbilt moved it to New York City in 1867.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] One of the ten companies that formed the NYCRR was the Mohawk and Hudson Railroad, which was the first railroad in the state and the first successful steam railroad running regularly scheduled service in the country.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] While the key to Albany's economic prosperity in the 19th century was transportation, industry and business also played a role.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Largely thanks to the city's Dutch and German roots, beer was one of its biggest commodities.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Beverwyck Brewery, originally known as Quinn and Nolan (Nolan being mayor of Albany 1878–1883), was the last remaining brewer from that time when it closed in 1972.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The city's location at the east end of the Erie Canal gave it unparalleled access to both raw products and a captive customer base in the west.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany was known for its publishing houses, and to some extent, still is.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany was second only to Boston in the number of books produced for most of the 19th century.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Iron foundries in both the north and south ends of the city attracted thousands of immigrants to the city for industrial jobs.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Intricate wrought-iron details constructed in those years remain visible on what are now historic buildings.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The iron industry waned by the 1890s due to increased costs associated with a newly unionized workforce and the opening of mines in the Mesabi Range in Minnesota.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's other major exports during the 18th and 19th centuries were furs, wheat, meat, and lumber.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] By 1865, there were almost 4,000 saw mills in the Albany area and the Albany Lumber District was the largest lumber market in the nation.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The city was also home to a number of banks.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The Bank of Albany (1792–1861) was the second chartered bank in New York.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The city was the original home of the Albank (founded in 1820 as the Albany Savings Bank), KeyBank (founded in 1825 as the Commercial Bank of Albany), and Norstar Bank (founded as the State Bank of Albany in 1803).
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] American Express was founded in Albany in 1850 as an express mail business.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In 1871, the northwestern portion of Albany—west from Magazine Street—was annexed to the neighboring town of Guilderland after the town of Watervliet refused annexation of the territory.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In return for this loss, portions of Bethlehem and Watervliet were added to Albany.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Part of the land annexed to Guilderland was ceded back to Albany in 1910, setting up the current western border.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The train carrying the body of slain President Abraham Lincoln came through Albany on the way to Illinois and the ghostly image of that train remains.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany opened one of the first commercial airports in the world, and the first municipal airport in the United States, in 1908.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Originally on a polo field on Loudon Road, it moved to Westerlo Island in 1909 and remained there until 1928.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The Albany Municipal Airport—jointly owned by the city and county—was moved to its current location in Colonie in 1928.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] By 1916 Albany's northern and southern borders reached their modern courses; Westerlo Island, to the south, became the second-to-last annexation, which occurred in 1926.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Erastus Corning 2nd, arguably Albany's most notable mayor (and great-grandson of the former mayor of the same name), was elected in 1941.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] While Corning brought stability to the office of mayor, it is said even those who admire him greatly cannot come up with a sizable list of "major concrete Corning achievements." Corning is given credit for saving—albeit somewhat unintentionally—much of Albany's historic architecture.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] During the 1950s and 1960s, a time when federal aid for urban renewal was plentiful, Albany did not have growth in its economy or infrastructure.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] It lost more than 20 percent of its population during the Corning years, as people moved to newer housing in the suburbs, followed by most of the downtown businesses moving there as well.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] While cities across the country grappled with similar issues, the problems were magnified in Albany: interference from the Democratic political machine hindered progress considerably.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In 1960, the mayor sold the city's stake in the airport to the county, citing budget issues.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] It was known from then on as Albany County Airport until a massive upgrade and modernization project between 1996 and 1998, when it was rebranded Albany International Airport.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Governor Nelson Rockefeller (1959–1973) (R) tried to stimulate the city with new monumental architecture and large, government-sponsored building projects; he drove construction of the Empire State Plaza, SUNY Albany's uptown campus, and much of the W.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Averell Harriman State Office Building Campus.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany County Republican Chairman Joseph C.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Frangella once quipped, "Governor Rockefeller was the best mayor Albany ever had." Corning, although opposed to the project, was responsible for negotiating the payment plan for the Empire State Plaza.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Rockefeller did not want to be limited by the Legislature's power of the purse, so Corning devised a plan to have the county pay for the construction and have the state sign a lease-ownership agreement.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The state paid off the bonds until 2004.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] It was Rockefeller's only viable option, and he agreed.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Due to the clout Corning gained from the situation, he gained inclusion of the State Museum, a convention center, and a restaurant, back in the plans—ideas which Rockefeller had originally vetoed.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The county gained $35 million in fees and the city received $13 million for lost tax revenue.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Having the state offices in the city enabled it to keep good jobs and retain middle-class residents.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Another major project of the 1960s and 1970s was the construction of Interstate 787 and the South Mall Arterial.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] A proposed Mid-Crosstown Arterial never came to fruition.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] One of the project's main results was separating the city from the Hudson River.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] When Corning died in 1983, Thomas Whalen assumed the mayorship and was reelected twice.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] He encouraged redevelopment of historic structures and helped attract federal dollars earmarked for that purpose.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] What Corning had saved from destruction, Whalen refurbished for continued and new uses.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The Mayor's Office of Special Events was created in an effort to increase the number of festivals and artistic events in the city, including a year-long *Dongan Charter* tricentennial celebration in 1986.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Whalen is credited for an "unparalleled cycle of commercial investment and development" in Albany due to his "aggressive business development programs".
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Prior to the recession of the 1990s, downtown Albany was home to four Fortune 500 companies.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] After the death of Corning and the retirement of Congressman Sam Stratton, the political environment changed.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Long-term office holders became rare in the 1980s.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Local media began following the drama surrounding county politics (specifically that of the newly created county executive position); the loss of Corning (and eventually the machine) led to a lack of interest in city politics.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The election of Gerald Jennings was a surprise, and he served as mayor from 1994 until his retirement at the end of 2013.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] His tenure essentially ended the political machine that had been in place since the 1920s.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Many state workers were relocated from the Harriman State Office Campus to downtown, helping its retail businesses and vitality.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The first decade of the 21st century saw a real possibility for a long-discussed and controversial Albany Convention Center; it opened in 2017 with the goal of making Albany a viable location for large events hosted by statewide organizations.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany remains an important location for business presence, given its role as de facto seat of Tech Valley and being home to the state capitol.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Fortune 500 companies with offices in Albany include American Express, J.P.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Morgan and Chase, Merrill Lynch, General Electric, Verizon, Goldman Sachs, International Paper, and Key Bank.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany won the All-America City Award in both 1991 and 2009.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] is located at the extreme right of the image.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is about 135 miles (217 km) north of New York City on the Hudson River.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] It has a total area of 21.8 square miles (56 km2), of which 21.4 square miles (55 km2) is land and 0.4 square miles (1.0 km2) (1.8%) is water.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The city is bordered on the north by the town of Colonie (along with the village of Menands), on the west by the town of Guilderland, and on the south by the town of Bethlehem.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The former Foxes Creek, Beaver Kill, and Rutten Kill were diverted underground in the 19th century.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] There are four lakes within city limits: Buckingham Lake; Rensselaer Lake at the mouth of the Patroon Creek; Tivoli Lake, which was formed as a reservoir and once connected to the Patroon Creek; and Washington Park Lake, which was formed by damming the Beaver Kill.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The highest natural point in Albany is a USGS benchmark near the Loudonville Reservoir off Birch Hill Road, at 378 feet (115 m) above sea level.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The lowest point is at the Hudson River—which is still technically an estuary at Albany and is affected by the Atlantic tide—at an average of 2 feet (0.61 m) above sea level at low tide and 4 feet (1.2 m) at high tide.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The interior of Albany consists of rolling hills which were once part of the Albany Pine Bush, an area of pitch pine and scrub oak, and has arid, sandy soil that is a remnant of the ancient Lake Albany.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Due to development, the Pine Bush has shrunk from an original 25,000 to 6,000 acres (10,100 to 2,400 ha) today.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] A preserve was set up by the State Legislature in 1988 and is on the city's western edge, spilling into Guilderland and Colonie; it is the only sizable inland pine barrens sand dune ecosystem in the United States, and is home to many endangered species, including the Karner Blue butterfly.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is in the humid continental climate zone (Köppen climate classification: Dfa), and features cold, snowy winters, and hot, humid summers; the city experiences four distinct seasons.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is in plant hardiness zone 6a near downtown and along the shore of the Hudson and 5b at its western end.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany receives 40.7 inches (1,030 mm) of precipitation per year, with 138 days of at least 0.01 in (0.25 mm) of precipitation each year.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Snowfall is significant, totaling 59.4 inches (151 cm) per season, but with less accumulation than the lake effect areas to the north and west, as it is farther from Lake Ontario.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] However, Albany is close enough to the Atlantic coast to receive heavy snow from Nor'easters and the city occasionally receives Alberta clippers.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Winters can be very cold with fluctuating conditions; temperatures drop to 0 °F (−18 °C) or below on nine nights per annum.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Summers in Albany can contain stretches of excessive heat and humidity, with temperatures of 90 °F (32 °C) or hotter on nine days per year.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Due to the variety of its communities, Albany is often called a "city of neighborhoods." The neighborhoods of Albany include Arbor Hill; Center Square, "[an] eclectic mix of residential and commercial [buildings], including bars, night clubs, restaurants, and stores"; Pine Hills; and the South End.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Historically, Albany's population has been mixed.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] First dominated by Mohican and Mohawk people, then Dutch and Germans, it was overtaken by the British in the early 19th century.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Irish immigrants soon outnumbered most other ethnicities by the mid-19th century, and were followed by Italians and Poles.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In the mid-to-late 20th century, the African-American population increased with thousands of people from the rural South, as part of the Great Migration.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Until after the Revolution, Albany's population consisted mostly of ethnic Dutch descendants.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Settlers migrating from New England tipped the balance toward British ethnicity in the early 19th century.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Jobs on the turnpikes, canals, and railroads attracted floods of Irish immigrants in the early 19th century, especially in the 1840s during the Great Famine, solidifying the city's Irish base.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Michael Nolan became Albany's first Irish Catholic mayor in 1878, two years before Boston.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Polish and Italian immigrants began arriving in Albany in the wave of immigration in the latter part of the 19th century.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Their numbers were smaller than in many other eastern cities mainly because most had found manufacturing jobs at General Electric in Schenectady.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The Jewish community had been established early, with Sephardic Jewish members as part of the Beverwijck community.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Its population rose during the late 19th century, when many Ashkenazi Jews immigrated from eastern Europe.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In that period, there was also an influx of Chinese and east Asian immigrants, who settled in the downtown section of the city.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Many of their descendants have since moved to suburban areas.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Asian immigration all but halted after the Immigration Act of 1924.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany saw its last large immigration pattern as part of the Great Migration when many African Americans moved there from the American South before and after World War I to fill industrial positions and find other opportunities.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In the early years, African-Americans lived together with Italians, Jews, and other immigrants in the South End, where housing was older and less expensive.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The black community has grown as a proportion of the population since then; African Americans made up three percent of the city's population in 1950, six percent in 1960, 12 percent in 1970, and 30 percent in 2010.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The change in proportion is related mostly to middle-class white families moving to the suburbs and black families remaining within city limits during the same time period.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Since 2007, the number of Burmese refugees to Albany has increased.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The Burmese refugee community consists mostly of people of Karen ethnicity.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] An estimated 5,000 Burmese refugees reside in Albany as of January 2015.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Like most cities of comparable age and size, Albany has well-established Orthodox Christian, Roman Catholic, Protestant, and Jewish communities.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is home to the oldest Christian congregation in Upstate New York and the Mother Churches of two Christian dioceses.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] As of June 2010, eight churches or religious buildings in the city were listed on the National Register of Historic Places, one of which—St.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Peter's Episcopal Church on State Street—is a National Historic Landmark.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Established in 1642, the congregation of the First Church in Albany (Reformed), also known as the North Dutch Church (on North Pearl Street), is the second-oldest Reformed Church in America.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] As of 2023, the city was home to twelve Catholic churches and four Episcopal churches.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Despite its history of Christendom, in 2019 the Albany-Schenectady-Troy MSA was found to be among the most post-Christian cities in the United States in a study by Christian polling firm The Barna Group.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] A significant Jewish presence has existed in Albany as early as 1658.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] As of 2010, Albany is home to two Conservative synagogues, a Chabad-Lubavitch synagogue, an Orthodox synagogue, and two Reform synagogues.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is also home to one of the few Karaite synagogues outside Israel.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] As of 2008, the total membership in Albany's synagogues was estimated at 12,000–13,000, with half the members residing outside the city.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Since the early 2000s, there has been an increase in Orthodox Jews moving to Albany from the New York Metro area, largely due to cheaper housing prices and closer walking proximity to synagogues.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The Islamic community in Albany and its surrounding suburbs is represented by at least four major mosques in the region.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The Muslim population increased substantially starting in the late 2000s, with the arrival of many refugees from countries such as Iraq, Syria, and Afghanistan.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Exact numbers on religious denominations in Albany are not readily available.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Demographic statistics in the United States depend heavily on the United States Census Bureau, which cannot ask about religious affiliation as part of its decennial census.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] It does compile some national and statewide religious statistics, but these are not representative of a city the size of Albany.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] One report from 2000 offers religious affiliations for Albany County.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] According to the data, 59.2% of Albany County residents identified as Christian: 47% are Roman Catholic, 8.4% are mainline Protestants, 2.7% are Evangelical Protestants, and 1.1% are Eastern or Oriental Orthodox Christians.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Residents who practice Judaism make up 4.2% of the population and Muslims represent 0.2%.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] As of the 2020 census, Albany had a population of 99,224.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] 17.8% of residents were under the age of 18 and 13.3% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] For every 100 females there were 93.5 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 91.3 males age 18 and over.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] 100.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] There were 42,158 households in Albany, of which 21.8% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Of all households, 22.4% were married-couple households, 29.1% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 39.5% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] About 43.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] There were 48,031 housing units, of which 12.2% were vacant.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The homeowner vacancy rate was 2.7% and the rental vacancy rate was 7.8%.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] According to the 2020 American Community Survey, the Latino population was: 4.57% Puerto Rican, 1.45% Dominican, .84% Ecuadorian, .77% Mexican, .69% Salvadoran, .22% Cuban.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] As of the 2010 census, Albany's population density was 4,572.7 inhabitants per square mile (1,765.5/km2).
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] There were 46,362 housing units at an average density of 2,166.4 per square mile (836.5/km2); 5,205 of these units (11.2%) were vacant.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The racial makeup of the city residents was 52.3% white; 27% Black or African American; 0.06% Native American or Native Alaskan; 7.4% Asian; 0.1% Native Hawaiian or Pacific Islander; .06% from other races; and 3.6% from two or more races.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] A total of 9.2% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Non-Hispanic Whites were 52.0% of the population in 2010, compared to 87.0% in 1970.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] For every 100 females, there were 90.6 males.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 86.5 males.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Some 81.3% of the population had completed high school or earned an equivalency diploma.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] As of the 2000 census, the top five ancestry groups in the city were African American (27%), Irish (18.1%), Italian (12.4%), German (10.4%), and English (5.2%); (33.1%) of the population reported "other ancestries".
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is home to a Triqui language-speaking community of Mexican-Americans.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] There were 40,709 households in Albany in 2000, of which 22.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 25.3% were married couples living together, 16.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 54.8% were non-families.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] 41.9% of all households were made up of individuals, and 11.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The average household size was 2.11 and the average family size was 2.95.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The median income for a household in the city in 2000 was $96,713, and the median income for a family was $100,374 (male, year-round worker) and $91,052 (female, year-round worker).
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The per capita income for the city was $73,985.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] About 16.0% of families and 21.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including 28.8% of those under age 18 and 12.5% of those age 65 or over.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The rate of reported violent crimes for 2008 (1,095 incidents per 100,000 residents) were more than double the rate for similarly sized US cities.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Reported property crimes (4,669 incidents per 100,000 residents) were somewhat lower.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] With a 2013 Census-estimated population of 1.1 million, the eight county Capital District, encompassing Albany, Troy, Schenectady and Saratoga, is the third-most populous metropolitan region in the state.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Demographically speaking, the population of Albany and the Capital District mirrors the characteristics of the United States consumer population as a whole better than any other major municipality in the country.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] According to a 2004 study conducted by the Acxiom Corporation, Albany and its environs are the top-ranked standard test market for new business and retail products.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany, Rochester, and Syracuse all scored within the top five.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's violent crime rate was 10.03 per 1,000 residents in 2023, compared to 7.69 in Buffalo, 7.39 in Rochester, 8.22 in Syracuse, and 7.72 in New York City.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] New York State had statewide violent crime rate of 3.90 per 1,000 people in 2023.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's economy, along with that of the Capital District in general, is heavily dependent on government, health care, education, and more recently, technology.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Because of these typically steady economic bases, the local economy has been relatively immune to national economic recessions in the past.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In 2009, more than 25 percent of the city's population worked in government-related positions.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's estimated daytime population is more than 162,000.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Companies based in Albany include Trans World Entertainment, AMRI Global and Clough Harbour.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] In 2019, Albany had the fourth-highest amount of lawyers in its employment pool (7.5 lawyers per 1,000 jobs) compared to the rest of the nation, behind Washington, D.C., Trenton, New Jersey, and New York City, respectively.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Since the 2000s, the economy of Albany and the surrounding Capital District has been directed toward high technology, a growing fourth sector of the area's economic base.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] Tech Valley is a marketing name for the eastern part of New York State, encompassing Albany, the Capital District, and the Hudson Valley.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] The area's high technology ecosystem is supported by technologically focused academic institutions including Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute and the State University of New York Polytechnic Institute.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p01] A notable video game development cluster has grown in and around Albany starting in the 2010s.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's geographic situation—roughly equidistant from New York City to the south and Montreal to the north—makes it a convenient stop for nationally touring artists and acts.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Palace Theatre and The Egg are mid-sized forums for music, theater, and spoken-word performances; the Capital Repertory Theatre is smaller.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The MVP Arena is the city's largest musical venue for nationally and internationally prominent bands.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] It also hosts trade shows, sporting events, and other large gatherings.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] In recent years, the city's government has invested resources to cultivate venues and neighborhoods that attract after-hours business.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Madison Avenue, Pearl Street, Delaware Avenue and Lark Street are the most active entertainment areas in the city.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Many restaurants, clubs, and bars have opened since the mid-1990s, revitalizing areas that had once been abandoned and reclaiming old row houses, businesses, and a pump station.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Much of the bar restaurant scene features classic Irish Pubs.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Price Chopper Fabulous Fourth and Fireworks Festival at the Empire State Plaza celebrates Independence Day with musical performances and the region's largest fireworks display.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Chefs' Food & Wine Festival donates all net proceeds to deserving Albany Arts Organizations and is held the Thursday-Saturday preceding Martin Luther King Weekend.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Because of Albany's historical and political significance, the city has numerous museums, historical buildings, and historic districts.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is home to the New York State Museum, the New York State Library and the New York State Archives; all three facilities are in the Cultural Education Center at the south end of Empire State Plaza and are free to the public.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The USS *Slater* (DE-766), a decommissioned World War II destroyer escort that was restored in 1998, is a museum ship docked in the Hudson River at Quay Street.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] It is the only ship of its kind still afloat.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Heritage Area Visitors Center, at the corner of Clinton Avenue and Broadway at Quackenbush Square, hosts a museum, gift shop, and the Henry Hudson Planetarium.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] In early 2012, the Irish American Heritage Museum opened in downtown Albany.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The museum is home to exhibits highlighting the contributions of the Irish people in America.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is home to 57 listings on the National Register of Historic Places (NRHP) and five National Historic Landmarks.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Ten Broeck Mansion, a 1797 Federal-style mansion (later renovated in the Greek-Revival style) built for Abraham Ten Broeck (mayor of Albany 1779–1783 and 1796–1798) is a historic house museum and the headquarters of the Albany County Historical Association; it was added to the NRHP in 1971.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Later known as "Arbor Hill", it gave the current neighborhood its name.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has been the subject, inspiration, or location for many written and cinematic works.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Many non-fiction works have been written on the city.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] One of the city's more notable claims to fame is *Ironweed* (1983), the 1984 Pulitzer Prize-winning book by Albany native William Kennedy.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] *Ironweed* was the third in a series of books by Kennedy known as the "Albany Cycle".
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The elusive author Trevanian also grew up in Albany and wrote *The Crazyladies of Pearl Street* (2005), about a North Albany neighborhood along Pearl Street.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The book is considered a semi-autobiographical memoir.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] In 1987, the film version of *Ironweed* premiered at the Palace Theatre.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The movie starred Jack Nicholson and Meryl Streep, each of whom were nominated for Academy Awards for their performances; much of the filming was done on location in Albany.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Most recently the downtown area was the site of filming for the action-thriller *Salt*, starring Angelina Jolie, and the action-comedy *The Other Guys*, starring Will Ferrell and Mark Wahlberg.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Authors Herman Melville and Henry James lived with their families in Albany when young, before their careers.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] James identified his character Isabel Archer, the heroine of his novel *The Portrait of a Lady*, as being from Albany.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Gregory Maguire, author of *Wicked: The Life and Times of the Wicked Witch of the West* (adapted for the Broadway hit *Wicked*), grew up in North Albany and graduated from SUNY Albany.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Empire State Plaza, a collection of state agency office buildings, dominates almost any view of Albany.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Built between 1965 and 1978 at the hand of Governor Nelson A.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Rockefeller and architect Wallace Harrison, the complex is a powerful example of late American modern architecture and remains a controversial building project both for displacing city residents and for its architectural style.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The most recognizable aspect of the complex is the Erastus Corning Tower, the tallest building in New York outside of New York City.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Juxtaposed at the north end of the Plaza is the 19th-century New York State Capitol, the seat of the New York State Legislature and the home of the Governor's office.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's initial architecture incorporated many Dutch influences, followed soon after by those of the English.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Quackenbush House, a Dutch Colonial brick mansion, was built c.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] 1736; Schuyler Mansion, a Georgian-style mansion, was built in 1765; and the oldest building in Albany is the 1728 Van Ostrande-Radliff House at 48 Hudson Avenue.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's housing varies greatly, with mostly row houses in the older sections of town, closer to the river.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Housing type quickly changes as one travels westward, beginning with two-family homes of the late 19th century, and one-family homes built after World War II in the western end of the city.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany City Hall, designed by Henry Hobson Richardson, was opened in 1883.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Capitol was opened in 1899 (after 32 years of construction) at a cost of $25 million, making it the most expensive government building at the time.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's Union Station, a major Beaux-Arts design, was under construction at the same time; it opened in 1900.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] In 1912, the Beaux-Arts styled New York State Department of Education Building opened on Washington Avenue near the Capitol.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] It has a classical exterior, which features a block-long white marble colonnade.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The 1920s brought the Art Deco movement, which is illustrated by the Home Savings Bank Building (1927) on North Pearl Street and the Alfred E.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Smith Building (1930) on South Swan Street, two of Albany's tallest high-rises.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Architecture from the 1960s and 1970s is well represented in the city, especially at the W.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Averell Harriman State Office Building Campus (1950s and 1960s) and on the uptown campus of the University at Albany (1962–1971).
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The state office campus was planned in the 1950s by governor W.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Averell Harriman to offer more parking and easier access for state employees.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The uptown SUNY campus was built in the 1960s under Governor Rockefeller on the site of the city-owned Albany Country Club.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Straying from the popular open campus layout, SUNY Albany has a centralized building layout with administrative and classroom buildings at center surrounded by four student housing towers.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The design called for much use of concrete and glass, and the style has slender, round-topped columns and pillars reminiscent of those at Lincoln Center in New York City.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Downtown has seen a revival in recent decades, often considered to have begun with Norstar Bank's renovation of the former Union Station as its corporate headquarters in 1986.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Knickerbocker Arena (MVP Arena) was originally slated for suburban Colonie, but was instead built downtown and opened in 1990.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has teams in two top-level professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada (New York Atlas, and Albany Firebirds), and several minor-league sports teams with varying levels of support.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Devils were a minor league ice hockey team that moved to the city for the 2010–11 season.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] They played in the American Hockey League and were affiliated with the New Jersey Devils of the National Hockey League.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Devils replaced the Albany River Rats, who played in the Capital Region from 1990 to 2010, when they relocated to Charlotte, North Carolina.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Devils moved to Binghamton, New York in 2017.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Times Union Center has previously hosted arena football teams including the Albany Firebirds in the Arena Football League (AFL) from 1990 to 2000 and then a team originally known as the Albany Conquest and later the Firebirds in the af2, the AFL's developmental league, from 2002 to 2009.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Empire played in the AFL from 2018 through the 2019 season when the league folded.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] A new Albany Empire was relaunched in the National Arena League for the 2021 season.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] In 2023, Antonio Brown bought the team; after a series of problems with payments and personnel, the NAL suspended the franchise in the middle of the 2023 season.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] A relaunched Albany Firebirds franchise began playing in 2024.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Tri-City ValleyCats short season minor league baseball team have played at the Joseph L.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Bruno Stadium on the Hudson Valley Community College campus in North Greenbush since 2002.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Prior to the ValleyCats' arrival, the Albany-Colonie Diamond Dogs (1995–2002) played at Heritage Park in Colonie; due to financial pressures, and facing impending competition from the ValleyCats, the franchise folded in 2002.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Legends (International Basketball League), played in the Washington Avenue Armory from 2010 to 2014 before moving to Schenectady.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Patroons have played at the Armory on and off since 1982 and currently play in The Basketball League.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] With the large number of local colleges and universities around Albany, college sports are popular.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The University at Albany's Great Danes play at the Division I level in all sports.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The football team is a member of the Coastal Athletic Association while all other sports teams play as members of the America East Conference.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] In 2006, UAlbany became the first SUNY-affiliated school to send a team to the NCAA Division I men's basketball tournament.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Siena Saints saw a rise in popularity after their men's basketball team made it to the NCAA Tournament in 2008, 2009, and 2010.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] All 18 Saints teams are Division I and play in the Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Although Siena's campus is in nearby Colonie, the men's basketball team plays at the Times Union Center.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] UAlbany hosted the New York Giants training camp from 1996 to 2012.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] On February 23, 2021, it was announced that the National Lacrosse League (NLL) would return to the city with the relocation of the New England Black Wolves.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The team was named the Albany FireWolves on April 15, 2021.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] This is the second NLL team to be based in the area; the first, the Albany Attack, played in the city from 2000 to 2003.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] In 2023, the Premier Lacrosse League (PLL) selected cities for their 8 franchises, and Albany was chosen as the primary home for the New York Atlas.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] In 2024, the Albany Firebirds began playing in the AFL at the MVP Arena.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] After one season in the AFL, the team moved to the AF1.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The 518 Ballers (American Basketball Association) have played at Our Savior's Christian School since 2023.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has more than 60 public parks and recreation areas.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Washington Park was organized as the Middle Public Square in 1806.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Its current location has been public property since the *Dongan Charter* of 1686 gave the city title to all property not privately owned.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Washington Park was designed by John Bogart and John Cuyler in 1870, and opened for public use the following year.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The original lake house, designed by Frederick W.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The park had previously been used as a cemetery; its graves were moved to Albany Rural Cemetery.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Washington Park is a popular place to exercise and play sports; skate during the winter; people-watch during Tulip Fest; and attend plays at the amphitheater during the summer.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Other parks in Albany include Lincoln Park, Buckingham Park, the Corning Preserve, the Albany Skyway and the Pine Bush.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Lincoln Park, southwest of the Empire State Plaza, was organized in 1886 and was originally known as Beaver Park.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Today, the park has a pool that is open during the summer months.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Buckingham Lake Park is between Manning Boulevard and Route 85 in the Buckingham Pond neighborhood; it contains a pond with fountains, a footpath, a playground, and picnic tables.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Riverfront Park at the Corning Preserve has an 800-seat amphitheatre that hosts events in non-winter months, most notably the *Alive at 5* summer concert series.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Preserve's visitors center details the ecology of the Hudson River and the local environment.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The park has a bike trail and boat launch and was effectively separated from downtown by Interstate 787 until the opening of the Hudson River Way in 2002.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Other public parks include Westland Hill Park, Hoffman Park, Beverwyck Park, and Liberty Park, today a small circular grassy patch in downtown on Hudson Avenue, which is Albany's oldest park.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Ridgefield Park is home to the clay courts of the Albany Tennis Club, one of the oldest tennis clubs in the United States.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The municipal golf course, New Course at Albany, was constructed in 1929 as the Albany Municipal Golf Course, later renamed the Capital Hills at Albany, and remodeled in 1991.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has a strong mayor-council government, which functions under the Dongan Charter, granted by colonial governor Thomas Dongan in 1686 when Albany was incorporated.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] A revised charter was adopted by referendum in 1998, but was legally reckoned as an amendment to the Dongan Charter.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] This gives Albany the distinction of having the oldest active city charter in the United States and "arguably the longest-running instrument of municipal government in the Western Hemisphere." The mayor, who is elected every four years, heads the executive branch of city government.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The current mayor, Kathy Sheehan, was first elected in 2013.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Common Council represents the legislative branch of city government and is made up of fifteen council members (each elected from one ward) and an at-large Common Council President.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The current president is Corey Ellis; he began his term in January 2018.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] While Albany has its own city government, it has also been the seat of Albany County since the county's formation in 1683 and the capital of New York since 1797.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] As such, the city is home to all branches of the county and state governments, as well as its own.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany City Hall sits on Eagle Street, opposite the State Capitol, and the Albany County Office Building is on State Street.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The state government has offices scattered throughout the city.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is in the 20th Congressional district, represented by Paul Tonko (D) in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The city is represented by Chuck Schumer (D) and Kirsten Gillibrand (D) in the United States Senate.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] On the state level, the city is in the 44th district in the New York Senate, represented by Patricia Fahy (D).
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] In the New York Assembly, western Albany is in the 109th district, represented by Gabriella Romero (D) while downtown and eastern Albany are in the 108th district, represented by John T.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] As the seat of Albany County, the city is the location of the county's courts including Family Court, County Court, Surrogate Court, Supreme Court, and New York Court of Appeals.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is the site of a federal courthouse that houses the United States District Court for the Northern District of New York.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's politics have been dominated by the Democratic Party since the 1920s; Daniel (Uncle Dan) O'Connell established a political machine in the city with the election of William Stormont Hackett as mayor in 1922.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Prior to that, William Barnes Jr. had set up a Republican machine in the 1890s.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Barnes' success is attributed to the fact that he owned two newspapers in Albany and that he was the grandson of Thurlow Weed, the influential newspaper publisher and political boss.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] O'Connell's organization overcame Barnes' in 1922 and survived well into the 1980s (even after his death).
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] In many instances, votes were outright bought.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Gerald Jennings' upset in the 1993 Democratic mayoral primary over Harold Joyce, who had the Democratic Party's formal endorsement and had only recently been its county chairman, is often cited as the end of the O'Connell era in Albany.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] In the early 21st century, Albany continued to be dominated by the Democratic Party.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Democratic Party enrollment in the city was 38,862 in 2009, while Republican enrollment was 3,487.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] As of 2022, every elected city position had been held by a Democrat since 1931.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] In November 2013, Kathy Sheehan became the first woman to be elected Mayor of Albany.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The City School District of Albany (CSDA) operates the city's public school system, which consists of 17 schools and learning centers; in addition, there are 7 charter schools, including Green Tech Charter High School, and Albany Leadership High School.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] In the 2015–2016 school year, over 9,000 students were enrolled in the public school system.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The district had an average class size of 18, an 81-percent graduation rate, and a 5-percent dropout rate.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Although considered by the state to be one of the lowest-achieving high schools in New York, Albany High was listed as the nation's 976th best high school in a 2010 *Newsweek/Washington Post* report.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany also has a number of private schools, including the coed Bishop Maginn High School and Albany Free School; the all-boys Albany Academy; and the all-girls Academy of the Holy Names and Albany Academy for Girls.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Medical College (private), today part of Albany Medical Center, was founded in 1839.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany Law School (private) is the oldest law school in New York and the fourth-oldest in the country; it was opened in 1851.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] President William McKinley was an alumnus.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany College of Pharmacy and Health Sciences (private) is the second-oldest pharmacy school in New York and the fifteenth-oldest in the United States.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Normal School, one of the oldest teachers colleges in the United States, opened in 1844; it was later known as the State Teachers College.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] It eventually evolved into the University at Albany, also known as SUNY Albany (public), which inherited the Normal School's original downtown campus on Western Avenue.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The center of the campus moved to its current Uptown Campus in the west end of the city in 1970.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] SUNY Albany is a unit of the State University of New York and one of only four university centers in the system.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Other colleges and universities in Albany include Empire State College, The College of Saint Rose, Excelsior College, Maria College, Mildred Elley, and Sage College of Albany.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Nearby Hudson Valley Community College (HVCC) fills the community college niche in the Albany-Troy area.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The effect of the campuses on the city's population is substantial: Combining the student bodies of all the aforementioned campuses (except HVCC) results in 63,149 students, or almost 70 percent of the 2008 estimate of Albany's permanent population.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The *Times Union* is Albany's primary daily newspaper and the only one based close to the city; its headquarters moved from within city limits to suburban Colonie in the 1960s after a dispute with Mayor Corning over land needed for expansion.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Its circulation totals about 73,000 on weekdays and 143,000 on Sundays.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Serving Albany to a lesser degree are *The Daily Gazette*, based in Schenectady, and *The Record*, of Troy.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] *Metroland* is the alternative newsweekly in the area, publishing each Thursday, while *The Business Review* is a business weekly published each Friday.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The *Legislative Gazette*, another weekly newspaper, focuses exclusively on issues related to the Legislature and the state government.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] As of 2010, the Albany-Schenectady-Troy media market is the 63rd-largest in the country in terms of radio and the 57th-largest in terms of television audiences.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] It is a broadcast market with historical significance.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The pioneering influence of General Electric in Schenectady directly contributed to the area emerging as the birthplace of station-based television with WRGB; the station was also the first affiliate of NBC.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] In 1947, the region was home to the first independently owned and operated commercial FM radio station in the United States: W47A.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] WGY was the second commercial radio station in New York and the twelfth in the nation.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Capital District is home to ABC affiliate WTEN 10, CBS affiliate WRGB 6 (also operating CW affiliate WCWN 45), Fox affiliate WXXA 23, NBC affiliate WNYT 13 (also operating MyNetworkTV affiliate WNYA 51), and PBS member station WMHT 17.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Charter Communications hosts Spectrum News Capital Region, the area's only local 24-hour news channel.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Thruway is the most prominent highway serving Albany.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] From Albany westward, it is part of Interstate 90, connecting Albany with major cities such as Syracuse, Rochester and Buffalo.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] To the south, it becomes part of Interstate 87 and leads to New York City.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] A short un-tolled section of Interstate 90 extends around the northern and eastern portions of Albany before linking back up with the Berkshire extension of the Thruway, which leads to the Massachusetts Turnpike and ultimately to Boston.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] North of Albany, Interstate 87 follows the Northway to Canada at Champlain; Autoroute 15 continues into Quebec, linking Albany to Montreal.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Interstate 787 links downtown Albany to the southbound I-87/Thruway to the south, while to the north, it links with the free portion of Interstate 90 before continuing to Troy, Watervliet, Colonie, and Menands.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] By way of Route 7, I-787 connects to the Northway.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Since the closure of Union Station on Broadway, area passenger-rail service is provided by Amtrak at the Albany-Rensselaer station across the river in Rensselaer.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] In 2009, the station saw more than 720,000 passengers, making it Amtrak's second-busiest in New York, behind Manhattan's Penn Station.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Amtrak provides service south to New York City; north to Montreal, and Burlington (Vermont); west to Niagara Falls, Toronto and Chicago; and east to Boston.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's major airport is Albany International Airport in Colonie.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Major airline service to Albany includes service by: American Airlines, Delta Air Lines, Southwest Airlines, JetBlue Airways, and United Airlines; Million Air is the local fixed-base operator.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] In 2010, Albany had the highest average airfare in New York, though the per-mile cost on its busiest routes was second-lowest in the state.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The Capital District Transportation Authority (CDTA) provides bus service throughout Albany and the surrounding area, including Schenectady, Troy, and Saratoga Springs.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The city was once served by an urban streetcar service maintained by the United Traction Company.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] As in many American cities, after the advent of the automobile, light rail services declined in Albany and were replaced by bus and taxi services.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Greyhound Lines, Trailways, Peter Pan, Short Line, Vermont Translines, and Yankee Trails buses all serve a downtown terminal.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Low-cost curbside bus service from the SUNY Albany campus and the Rensselaer station is also provided by Megabus, with direct service to New York City.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Albany, long an important Hudson River port, today serves domestic and international ships and barges through the Port of Albany-Rensselaer, on both sides of the river.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The port has the largest mobile harbor crane in the state of New York.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Barge Canal, the ultimate successor of the Erie Canal, is in use today, largely by tourist and private boats.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] The city of Nijmegen, Netherlands connected with Albany following World War II.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] With the help of the Catholic university in Albany, the Catholic University of Nijmegen (Radboud University Nijmegen) rebuilt its partly destroyed library, with over 50,000 books being donated to the Dutch university.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] To show its gratitude for post-war assistance, the city sent Albany 50,000 tulip bulbs in 1948; this act led to the establishment of the annual Tulip Festival.
[src:albany-new-york/albany-new-york-p02] Most of the other connections were made in the 1980s during Mayor Whalen's term in office as part of his cultural expansion program.
